1. Introduction¶

This project analyzes data from the popular music streaming platform, Spotify. The following analyses types have been conducted along with appropriate viosualizations:

  • Descriptive Analysis
  • Comparative Analysis
  • Trend Analysis
  • Predictive Analysis
  • Exploratory Analysis
  • Behavorial ANalysis
  • Segment Analysis

%matplotlib inline
# Set up the figure size
plt.figure(figsize=(15, 12))

num_columns = ['duration_ms', 'year', 'acousticness', 'danceability', 'energy',
               'instrumentalness', 'liveness', 'loudness', 'speechiness', 'tempo',
               'valence', 'popularity']

# Loop through columns and create histograms
for i, col in enumerate(num_columns, 1):
    plt.subplot(4, 4, i)  # Create a grid of subplots
    sns.histplot(spotify_data[col], bins=30, kde=True)
    plt.title(f'Distribution of {col}')
    
plt.tight_layout()  # Adjust layout for better spacing
plt.show()

# boxplots and checking for outliers
plt.figure(figsize=(15, 10))

for i, col in enumerate(num_columns, 1):
    plt.subplot(4, 4, i)
    sns.boxplot(x=spotify_data[col])
    plt.title(f'Box Plot of {col}')

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Based on the descriptive statistics and visualizations conducted so far, we can derive the following insights from the Spotify dataset:

  • Boxplots indicate outliers in song duration, loudness, and energy, suggesting unusual tracks that stand out in the dataset.

  • Song popularity: (The popularity of a track is a value between 0 and 100, with 100 being the most popular) - right skewed distribution, suggesting most songs within this particular dataset have low popularity, with only a few tracks achieving high popularity scores - meaning a small percentage of tracks dominate listener engagement

  • Track duration: (track length in milliseconds) - broad range of song durations, but extreme values (outliers) suggest some very long or very short tracks.

Analyzing for the Popularity of Tracks Over the Years¶

In [33]:
# Create a new column for decades (e.g., 1990-1999, 2000-2009, etc.)
spotify_data['decade'] = (spotify_data['year'] // 10) * 10

# Group by decade and calculate avg popularity, median popularity, and song count
decade_trend = spotify_data.groupby('decade').agg(
    avg_popularity=('popularity', 'mean'),
    median_popularity=('popularity', 'median'),
    song_count=('popularity', 'count')
).reset_index()

# Set figure size
plt.figure(figsize=(12,6))

# Bubble Chart with Decade Binning
sns.scatterplot(data=decade_trend, x='decade', y='avg_popularity', size='song_count', sizes=(50, 1000), alpha=0.6, legend=False)

# Line plot to show the trend of average popularity
sns.lineplot(data=decade_trend, x='decade', y='avg_popularity', color='blue', linewidth=2, label='Avg Popularity')

# Line plot to show the trend of median popularity
sns.lineplot(data=decade_trend, x='decade', y='median_popularity', color='red', linewidth=2, linestyle='dashed', label='MedianPopularity')

# Labels and Title
plt.xlabel("Decade")
plt.ylabel("Popularity Score")
plt.title("Popularity Trends Over the Decades (Bubble = Number of Songs)")
plt.xticks(np.arange(decade_trend['decade'].min(), decade_trend['decade'].max() + 10, 10))  # Ensure proper decade labels
plt.show()

Correlation Analysis¶

  • Dependent variable - Popularity.
  • Independent variable (numerical ones) - Acousticness, Danceability, Energy, Instrumentalness, Liveness, Loudness, Speechiness, Tempo, Valence.
In [34]:
# Selecting numerical columns for correlation analysis
correlation_features = [
    'popularity', 'duration_ms', 'acousticness', 'danceability', 'energy', 'instrumentalness',
    'liveness', 'loudness', 'speechiness', 'tempo', 'valence'
]

# Compute the correlation matrix
correlation_matrix = spotify_data[correlation_features].corr()

# Visualizing the correlation matrix as a heatmap
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.heatmap(correlation_matrix, annot=True, cmap='coolwarm', fmt=".2f", linewidths=0.5)

# Formatting the heatmap
plt.title("Correlation Matrix of Song Features and Popularity")
plt.show()

From the heatmap, we can infer:

  • Highly danceable, energetic, and loud songs tend to be slightly more popular (moderate positive correlation).
  • Acoustic and instrumental songs are less favored by listeners (negative correlation).
  • Tempo and valence do not play a significant role in determining popularity (weak positive correlation, suggesting song speed or emotional positivity does not strongly determine success).
  • Liveness and speech-heavy songs have minimal impact on popularity (weak/ neutral connection).

from scipy.stats import ttest_ind, f_oneway
# T-Test: Explicit vs. Non-Explicit Songs
explicit_songs = spotify_data[spotify_data['explicit'] == 1]['popularity']
non_explicit_songs = spotify_data[spotify_data['explicit'] == 0]['popularity']
t_stat_explicit, p_value_explicit = ttest_ind(explicit_songs, non_explicit_songs, equal_var=False)

# Calculate Cohen’s d for effect size (T-Test)
cohen_d_explicit = (explicit_songs.mean() - non_explicit_songs.mean()) / np.sqrt(
    (explicit_songs.var() + non_explicit_songs.var()) / 2)

# T-Test: Major vs. Minor Mode Songs
major_songs = spotify_data[spotify_data['mode'] == 1]['popularity']
minor_songs = spotify_data[spotify_data['mode'] == 0]['popularity']
t_stat_mode, p_value_mode = ttest_ind(major_songs, minor_songs, equal_var=False)

# Calculate Cohen’s d for effect size (T-Test)
cohen_d_mode = (major_songs.mean() - minor_songs.mean()) / np.sqrt(
    (major_songs.var() + minor_songs.var()) / 2)

# ANOVA Test: Popularity Across Different Musical Keys
popularity_by_key = [spotify_data[spotify_data['key'] == k]['popularity'] for k in sorted(spotify_data['key'].unique())]
f_stat_key, p_value_key = f_oneway(*popularity_by_key)

# Calculate Eta-Squared for effect size (ANOVA)
ss_between = sum(len(group) * (group.mean() - spotify_data['popularity'].mean())**2 for group in popularity_by_key)
ss_total = sum((spotify_data['popularity'] - spotify_data['popularity'].mean())**2)
eta_squared = ss_between / ss_total  # Effect size for ANOVA

# Print All Test Results Together
print("\n **T-Test for Popularity of Explicit vs. Non-Explicit Songs**")
print(f"T-statistic: {t_stat_explicit:.3f}, P-value: {p_value_explicit:.5f}, Cohen's d: {cohen_d_explicit:.3f}")
print("Significant difference" if p_value_explicit < 0.05 else "No significant difference")

print("\n **T-Test for Popularity of Major vs. Minor Mode Songs**")
print(f"T-statistic: {t_stat_mode:.3f}, P-value: {p_value_mode:.5f}, Cohen's d: {cohen_d_mode:.3f}")
print("Significant difference" if p_value_mode < 0.05 else "No significant difference")

print("\n **ANOVA Test for Popularity Across Musical Keys**")
print(f"F-statistic: {f_stat_key:.3f}, P-value: {p_value_key:.5f}, Eta-Squared: {eta_squared:.3f}")
print("Significant difference" if p_value_key < 0.05 else "No significant difference")

# Visualizations of the three plots side by side
fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(18, 5))

# Explicit vs. Non-Explicit Popularity (Boxplot)
sns.boxplot(x=spotify_data['explicit'], y=spotify_data['popularity'], ax=axes[0], palette="coolwarm", hue=spotify_data['explicit'])
axes[0].set_xticks([0, 1])
axes[0].set_xticklabels(['Non-Explicit', 'Explicit'])
axes[0].set_xlabel("Explicit Content")
axes[0].set_ylabel("Popularity Score")
axes[0].set_title("Popularity of Explicit vs. Non-Explicit Songs")
axes[0].legend_.remove()  # Remove legend

# Major vs. Minor Mode Popularity (Boxplot)
sns.boxplot(x=spotify_data['mode'], y=spotify_data['popularity'], ax=axes[1], palette="viridis", hue=spotify_data['mode'])
axes[1].set_xticks([0, 1])
axes[1].set_xticklabels(['Minor', 'Major'])
axes[1].set_xlabel("Mode (Musical Scale)")
